    "summary": "The Battle of Kursk, fought in July–August 1943 in southern Russia, was the largest tank battle in history and the last major German offensive on the Eastern Front. Following the catastrophic German defeat at [[event:2658|Stalingrad]] the previous winter, Germany launched Operation Citadel to eliminate a large Soviet salient (bulge) around the city of Kursk. The Soviets, forewarned by intelligence (including through the British Ultra program), prepared an elaborate defensive network of trenches, minefields, and anti-tank positions. German armored forces suffered severe losses attempting to break through these defenses.\n\nAfter eight days of failed offensive operations, the German attack was halted. The battle included the Prokhorovka tank engagement on July 12, often cited (though with some historical debate about exact losses) as the largest tank battle of the war. The Soviet counteroffensives that followed, Operations Kutuzov and Rumyantsev, drove the Germans back and liberated Orel and Kharkov. After Kursk, Germany never regained strategic initiative on the Eastern Front.\n\nKursk confirmed that the Soviet military had overcome its catastrophic early-war deficiencies and could now match and exceed German operational capability. The enormous industrial output of Soviet arms production, aided by American Lend-Lease supplies, underpinned this recovery. The subsequent Soviet advances accelerated through 1943–1944, eventually driving German forces entirely out of Soviet territory.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Kursk",
